The expression `not(X=&#39;value&#39;)` returns true if the set of nodes selected by X does not include a node whose string value is equal to `value`. This includes the case where the set of nodes selected by X is empty, that is, where the node is absent.

Now the question is, what do you want your expression to return? If you want it to return the relevant element if it exists and has the required value, or an empty node-set otherwise, then you can simply write

    //personName[. = &#39;novice&#39;]

If you want to return a boolean that tells you whether such a node exists, you can write

    boolean(//personName[. = &#39;novice&#39;])

In fact you can shorten this to

    //personName = &#39;novice&#39;

though I personally find this less clear, and it has the disadvantage that you can&#39;t apply the same contraction to more complex predicates like

    //personName[starts-with(., &#39;novice&#39;)]

If you want the inverse (return true if the element does not exist or does not have the right value), then

    not(//personName[. = &#39;novice&#39;])

